{{Distinguish|Computer keyboard}} 
A '''keyboard computer''' is a computer which contains all of the regular components of a [[personal computer]], except for a screen, in the same housing as the keyboard. The power supply is typically external and connects to the computer via an [[adapter]] cable. The motherboard is specially designed to fit inside, and the device is larger than most standard keyboards. Additional peripheral components such as a [[Computer monitor|monitor]] are connected to the computer via external [[Computer port (hardware)|ports]]. Usually no or only a minimum of storage devices is built in.

Most home computers of the late 1970s and during the 1980s were keyboard computers, the [[Commodore VIC-20]] and the [[Atari ST]] being prime examples. While this form factor went out of style around 1990 in favour for more standard PC setups, some notable [[x86]] keyboard computers have been built, like the [[Olivetti]] [[Prodest PC1]] in 1988<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Olivetti PC1|encyclopedia=Old-Computers.com|url=http://www.old-computers.com/museum/computer.asp?c=182&st=1|accessdate=2014-09-18}}</ref> and the Schneider EuroPC Series between 1988 and 1995.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Schneider Euro PC|encyclopedia=Haus der Computerspiele|url=http://www.classiccomputer.de/ams/scheuropc.htm|accessdate=2014-09-18}}</ref> [[Cybernet Manufacturing]] is still producing similar devices, using [[Intel]] [[Quad Core]] [[Central processing unit|processors]].{{citation needed|date=August 2010}}

Newer developments include the [[Commodore 64#Brand re-use|Commodore 64 WebIt]] by Tulip, the [[Asus Eee Keyboard]],<ref name="register1">{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/03/02/asus_hostage/|title=Asus assures no more delays for keyboard-computer|first=Joe|last=Fay|publisher=The Register|newspaper=The Register|date=2010-03-02|accessdate=2010-08-26}}</ref><ref name="press release">{{cite news|url=http://www.asus.com/News/PAT9g8UsynfYyxiN/|title=Asus Eee Keyboard Press Release|date=2010-05-01|accessdate=2013-06-05}}</ref> which uses an [[Intel Atom]] processor, and optionally [[Solid-state drive|solid state]] hard drives.<ref name="specs">{{cite news|url=http://www.bit-tech.net/hardware/peripherals/2010/08/02/asus-eee-keyboard-pc-review/1|title=ASUS Eee Keyboard PC Review|publisher=BitTech|date=2010-08-02|accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> Or designs like the Commodore [[Invictus PC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.netbookhelden.de/commodore-invictus-noch-ein-computer-im-tastatur-format/|title=Commodore Invictus|publisher=Notebookhelden|date=2010-06-02|accessdate=2014-09-18}}</ref>

