{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}
'''Mimetas''' is a privately owned biotechnology company developing human [[organ-on-a-chip]] tissue models and products for [[drug development]]. The company also is involved in the testing of chemicals along with food and [[personalized medicine]] applications. The [http://mimetas.com company] is based in [[Leiden]] and [[Enschede]], The Netherlands and in [[Rockville, Maryland|Rockville]] (MD), USA. Mimetas was founded in 2011 by Paul Vulto, Jos Joore, Bas Trietsch and Thomas Hankemeier.<ref>{{cite web|title=Launch of organs-on-a-chip|url=http://www.research.leiden.edu/news/launch-of-organs-on-a-chip.html|website=Leiden University|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> The company is co-led by Joore and Vulto as Managing Directors.
== Technology == [http://mimetas.com Mimetas] develops microfluidic tissue culture technology based on its proprietary OrganoPlate platform<ref name="Nature Medicine organ on a chip article">{{cite journal|title=Channeling chip power: Tissue chips are being put to the test by industry|journal=Nature Medicine|date=2 Feb 2017|volume=23|pages=138–140|doi=10.1038/nm0217-138|url=http://www.nature.com/nm/journal/v23/n2/full/nm0217-138.html|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> that supports 3-dimensional tissue culture under continuous perfusion, with membrane-free co-culture in a standard 384-well plate format.<ref name="Trietsch et al Lab on a Chip">{{cite journal|title=Microfluidic titer plate for stratified 3D cell culture|journal=Lab on a Chip|date=26 Jul 2013|volume=13|pages=3548–3554|doi=10.1039/C3LC50210D|url=http://pubs.rsc.org/en/Content/ArticleLanding/2013/LC/c3lc50210d#!divAbstract|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> This renders the technology suitable for low- to high-throughput screening applications.<ref name="Wevers et al Scientific Reports">{{cite journal|title=High-throughput compound evaluation on 3D networks of neurons and glia in a microfluidic platform|journal=Scientific Reports|date=9 Dec 2016|volume=6|doi=10.1038/srep38856|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/srep38856|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> Mimetas develops a range of tissue- and disease models, including kidney toxicity and disease models,<ref name="Tr in Biotech Kidney">{{cite journal|title=Kidney-on-a-Chip Technology for Drug-Induced Nephrotoxicity Screening|journal=Trends in Biotechnology|date=Feb 2016|volume=34|issue=2|pages=156–170|doi=10.1016/j.tibtech.2015.11.001|url=http://www.cell.com/trends/biotechnology/abstract/S0167-7799(15)00229-2|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> iPSC-derived neuronal brain tissue models<ref name="Wevers et al Scientific Reports" /> and liver models.<ref name="Trietsch et al Lab on a Chip" />
== History == The original idea for the foundation of Mimetas was raised in 2010 by Vulto and Joore, who envisioned creating the tissue equivalent of a microarray for massive parallel testing of therapeutic compounds. The idea was based on meniscus pinning technology, originally developed by Vulto, during his affiliations with Silicon Biosystems (Bologna, IT), now part of the [[Menarini]] Group and the Institute for Microsystems Engineering (IMTEK) of the [[University of Freiburg]] (GER). Mimetas was established in close collaboration with the group of Thomas Hankemeier of the [[Leiden University]], with essential contributions of Bas Trietsch who serves as Director of Research. Since its official incorporation in 2013, the company collaborates with a range of pharmaceutical companies on the development of tissue- and disease models, including [[Roche Pharmaceuticals|Roche]], [[BASF]], [[GlaxoSmithKline]], [[Pfizer]], [[Abbvie]], [[Janssen Pharmaceutica|Janssen]] and [[Biogen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ADAPTED|url=http://www.imi-adapted.eu/|website=Identifying new medicines to treat Alzheimer's Disease through greater understanding of the APOE gene|publisher=ADAPTED|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref><ref name="Neuratect">{{cite web|title=Neuratect|url=https://www.crackit.org.uk/challenge-17-neuratect|website=Crack It|publisher=NC3Rs|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref><ref name="Nephrotube">{{cite web|title=NephroTube|url=https://www.crackit.org.uk/challenge-15-nephrotube|website=Crack It|publisher=NC3Rs|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>
