'''Pieter Van den Abeele''' is a computer programmer,<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9593-5546033-3.html
|title=Sun poised to take open-source Solaris step 
|publisher=news.zdnet.com
|accessdate=2008-05-28
|last=
|first=
}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}
</ref> and the founder of the [[PowerPC]]-version of [[Gentoo Linux]], a foundation connected with a distribution of the [[Linux]] computer operating system.{{Clarify|date=February 2009}} He founded Gentoo for [[OS X]], for which he received a scholarship by [[Apple Computer]]. In 2004 Pieter was invited to the [[OpenSolaris]] pilot program and assisted [[Sun Microsystems]] with building a development eco-system around [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]]. Pieter was nominated for the OpenSolaris Community Advisory Board and managed a team of developers to make Gentoo available on the Solaris operating system as well. Pieter is a co-author of the [http://www.gentoo.org/doc/en/handbook/ Gentoo handbook].

The teams managed by Pieter Van den Abeele have shaped the [[PowerPC]] landscape with several "firsts". Gentoo/PowerPC was the first distribution to introduce PowerPC Live CDs. Gentoo also beat Apple to releasing a full [[64-bit]] PowerPC userland environment for the IBM [[PowerPC 970]] (G5) processor.

His Gentoo-based Home Media and Communication System, based on a [[Freescale Semiconductor]] [[PowerPC G4#PowerPC 7447.2F7457 .22Apollo 7.22|PowerPC 7447]] processor won the Best of Show award at the inaugural 2005 Freescale Technology Forum in Orlando, Florida. Pieter is also a member of the [[Power.org]] consortium and participates in committees and workgroups focusing on disruptive business plays around the [[Power Architecture]].

